Using the properties of the distribution of the sum, the expected value of the total time $E(T)$ is the sum of the individual means. Given the population mean is 20 minutes:

$$
\begin{aligned} 
\text{E}(T) &= \text{E}(X_1) + \text{E}(X_2) \\ 
&= 20 + 20 \\ 
&= 40 \text{ minutes} 
\end{aligned}
$$

This calculation earns the first method mark (**M1**).

The question specifies we should assume the population mean ($\mu$) is $20$ minutes for each task. The expected value of the sum is the sum of the expected values:

$$
\begin{aligned} 
\text{E}(T) &= \text{E}(X_1) + \text{E}(X_2) \\ 
\text{E}(T) &= 20 + 20 \\ 
\text{E}(T) &= 40 \text{ minutes} 
\end{aligned}
$$

This gives us the mean of our new distribution.
